<h2 class="title">Population pyramides with R</h2>


<p>Examples of static and interactive population pyramids using the packages <a href="http://docs.ggplot2.org/current/">ggplot2</a> and <a href="http://rcharts.io">rCharts</a> and population data from <a href="http://www.census.gov/population/international/data/idb/informationGateway.php">census.gov</a>.</p>
<hr />
<div id="overview" class="section level4">
<h4>Overview</h4>

<li><a href="#1">ggplot</a><br />
</li>

</div>
<div id="ggplot" class="section level4">
<h4><a name="1"></a> 1. ggplot</h4>
<blockquote>
<p><a name="1.2.a"></a> US Census Bureau’s International Data Base</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Start by installing the following packages.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>install.packages(&quot;XML&quot;)
install.packages(&quot;reshape2&quot;)
install.packages(&quot;plyr&quot;)
install.packages(&quot;ggplot2&quot;)</code></pre>
<p>Then load the installed packages into the active workspace and source some useful functions from my website.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>library(XML)
library(reshape2)
library(plyr)
library(ggplot2)
source('http://klein.uk/R/Viz/pyramids.R')</code></pre>
<p>The following function <code>getAgeTable</code> grabs the required population data from the US Census Bureau’s <a href="http://www.census.gov/population/international/data/idb/informationGateway.php">International Data Base</a> and outputs a data frame in the right format for <code>ggplot2</code>.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>popGHcens &lt;- getAgeTable(country = &quot;QA&quot;, year = 2015)

pyramidGH &lt;- ggplot(popGHcens, aes(x = Age, y = Population, fill = Gender)) + 
  geom_bar(data = subset(popGHcens, Gender == &quot;Female&quot;), stat = &quot;identity&quot;) + 
  geom_bar(data = subset(popGHcens, Gender == &quot;Male&quot;), stat = &quot;identity&quot;) + 
  scale_y_continuous(labels = paste0(as.character(c(seq(2, 0, -1), seq(1, 2, 1))), &quot;m&quot;)) + 
  coord_flip()
pyramidGH</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," title alt width="672" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /></p>
<blockquote>
<p><a name="1.2.b"></a> 10% sample of 2010 Ghana population census</p>
</blockquote>
<p>In an next step, let us try to use the above code snippets to produce the population pyramid for Ghana based on the 2010 census.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>## load the individual-level age data from the 2010 census
load(url(&quot;http://klein.uk/R/Viz/popGH.RData&quot;))

## cut the age variable into age groups with 5-year intervals
popGH$AGEcut &lt;- cut(popGH$AGE, breaks = seq(0, 100, 5), right = FALSE) 
popGH$Population &lt;- 10 ## each sampled respondent represents 10 individuals
popGH$Gender &lt;- popGH$SEX

## aggregate the data by gender and age group
popGH &lt;- aggregate(formula = Population ~ Gender + AGEcut, data = popGH, FUN = sum)

## sort data by first by gender, then by age groups
popGH &lt;- with(popGH, popGH[order(Gender,AGEcut),])

## for simplicity, add the age group labels we used in popGHcens above
popGH$Age &lt;- rep(unique(popGHcens$Age)[1:20], 2)

## only use the three variables age, gender and population from the popGH data
popGH &lt;- popGH[,c(&quot;Age&quot;,&quot;Gender&quot;,&quot;Population&quot;)]

## barplots for male populations goes to the left (thus negative sign)
popGH$Population &lt;- ifelse(popGH$Gender == &quot;Male&quot;, -1*popGH$Population, popGH$Population)

## pyramid charts are two barcharts with axes flipped
pyramidGH2 &lt;- ggplot(popGH, aes(x = Age, y = Population, fill = Gender)) + 
  geom_bar(data = subset(popGH, Gender == &quot;Female&quot;), stat = &quot;identity&quot;) +
  geom_bar(data = subset(popGH, Gender == &quot;Male&quot;), stat = &quot;identity&quot;) + 
  scale_y_continuous(labels = paste0(as.character(c(seq(2, 0, -1), seq(1, 2, 1))), &quot;m&quot;)) + 
  coord_flip()
pyramidGH2</code></pre>

<div id="rcharts" class="section level4">
<h4><a name="2"></a> 2. rcharts</h4>
<p>The package <code>rCharts</code> requires that you have <a href="https://cran.r-project.org/bin/windows/Rtools/">Rtools</a> installed in addition to base R. The <code>rCharts</code> package is not available on <a href="https://cran.r-project.org/">CRAN</a> but can be installed and loaded from <a href="https://github.com/ramnathv/rCharts">GitHub</a> as follows</p>
<pre class="r"><code>install.packages(&quot;devtools&quot;)
devtools::install_github(&quot;ramnathv/rCharts&quot;)
library(rCharts)</code></pre>
<p>Plot your pyramid chart by using your country code (e.g. Ghana = <code>'GH'</code>) and specifying the colors and years you want to plot.</p>
<p><strong>2.A. Stacked pyramid, by row</strong></p>
<pre class="r"><code>popGH2 &lt;- getAgeTable2(country = 'IN', year = 2014)
n1 &lt;- nPyramid(dat = popGH2, colors = c('blue', 'silver'))
n1</code></pre>

,"ord":82,"Year":2030,"Gender":"Female","Population":517391,"gencode":2},{"Age":"95-99","ord":83,"Year":2030,"Gender":"Female","Population":226268,"gencode":2},{"Age":"100+","ord":84,"Year":2030,"Gender":"Female","Population":60099,"gencode":2},{"Age":"0-4","ord":85,"Year":2040,"Gender":"Female","Population":1822423,"gencode":2},{"Age":"5-9","ord":86,"Year":2040,"Gender":"Female","Population":1874006,"gencode":2},{"Age":"10-14","ord":87,"Year":2040,"Gender":"Female","Population":1923278,"gencode":2},{"Age":"15-19","ord":88,"Year":2040,"Gender":"Female","Population":1976657,"gencode":2},{"Age":"20-24","ord":89,"Year":2040,"Gender":"Female","Population":2028761,"gencode":2},{"Age":"25-29","ord":90,"Year":2040,"Gender":"Female","Population":2080153,"gencode":2},{"Age":"30-34","ord":91,"Year":2040,"Gender":"Female","Population":2089158,"gencode":2},{"Age":"35-39","ord":92,"Year":2040,"Gender":"Female","Population":2041724,"gencode":2},{"Age":"40-44","ord":93,"Year":2040,"Gender":"Female","Population":1976584,"gencode":2},{"Age":"45-49","ord":94,"Year":2040,"Gender":"Female","Population":1959100,"gencode":2},{"Age":"50-54","ord":95,"Year":2040,"Gender":"Female","Population":2006993,"gencode":2},{"Age":"55-59","ord":96,"Year":2040,"Gender":"Female","Population":2013748,"gencode":2},{"Age":"60-64","ord":97,"Year":2040,"Gender":"Female","Population":1930718,"gencode":2},{"Age":"65-69","ord":98,"Year":2040,"Gender":"Female","Population":2117671,"gencode":2},{"Age":"70-74","ord":99,"Year":2040,"Gender":"Female","Population":2047638,"gencode":2},{"Age":"75-79","ord":100,"Year":2040,"Gender":"Female","Population":1908609,"gencode":2},{"Age":"80-84","ord":101,"Year":2040,"Gender":"Female","Population":1641387,"gencode":2},{"Age":"85-89","ord":102,"Year":2040,"Gender":"Female","Population":1275462,"gencode":2},{"Age":"90-94","ord":103,"Year":2040,"Gender":"Female","Population":799510,"gencode":2},{"Age":"95-99","ord":104,"Year":2040,"Gender":"Female","Population":261391,"gencode":2},{"Age":"100+","ord":105,"Year":2040,"Gender":"Female","Population":89239,"gencode":2},{"Age":"0-4","ord":106,"Year":2050,"Gender":"Female","Population":1720413,"gencode":2},{"Age":"5-9","ord":107,"Year":2050,"Gender":"Female","Population":1782236,"gencode":2},{"Age":"10-14","ord":108,"Year":2050,"Gender":"Female","Population":1847881,"gencode":2},{"Age":"15-19","ord":109,"Year":2050,"Gender":"Female","Population":1898015,"gencode":2},{"Age":"20-24","ord":110,"Year":2050,"Gender":"Female","Population":1938147,"gencode":2},{"Age":"25-29","ord":111,"Year":2050,"Gender":"Female","Population":1991353,"gencode":2},{"Age":"30-34","ord":112,"Year":2050,"Gender":"Female","Population":2050328,"gencode":2},{"Age":"35-39","ord":113,"Year":2050,"Gender":"Female","Population":2103967,"gencode":2},{"Age":"40-44","ord":114,"Year":2050,"Gender":"Female","Population":2110674,"gencode":2},{"Age":"45-49","ord":115,"Year":2050,"Gender":"Female","Population":2056356,"gencode":2},{"Age":"50-54","ord":116,"Year":2050,"Gender":"Female","Population":1979938,"gencode":2},{"Age":"55-59","ord":117,"Year":2050,"Gender":"Female","Population":1945688,"gencode":2},{"Age":"60-64","ord":118,"Year":2050,"Gender":"Female","Population":1968040,"gencode":2},{"Age":"65-69","ord":119,"Year":2050,"Gender":"Female","Population":1939042,"gencode":2},{"Age":"70-74","ord":120,"Year":2050,"Gender":"Female","Population":1808538,"gencode":2},{"Age":"75-79","ord":121,"Year":2050,"Gender":"Female","Population":1885898,"gencode":2},{"Age":"80-84","ord":122,"Year":2050,"Gender":"Female","Population":1675618,"gencode":2},{"Age":"85-89","ord":123,"Year":2050,"Gender":"Female","Population":1341024,"gencode":2},{"Age":"90-94","ord":124,"Year":2050,"Gender":"Female","Population":871639,"gencode":2},{"Age":"95-99","ord":125,"Year":2050,"Gender":"Female","Population":430278,"gencode":2},{"Age":"100+","ord":126,"Year":2050,"Gender":"Female","Population":161759,"gencode":2}];
  var svg = dimple.newSvg("#" + opts.id, opts.width, opts.height);

  var myChart = new dimple.chart(svg, data);
  if (opts.bounds) {
    myChart.setBounds(opts.bounds.x, opts.bounds.y, opts.bounds.width, opts.bounds.height);//myChart.setBounds(80, 30, 480, 330);
  }
  //dimple allows use of custom CSS with noFormats
  if(opts.noFormats) { myChart.noFormats = opts.noFormats; };
  //for markimekko and addAxis also have third parameter measure
  //so need to evaluate if measure provided
  
  //function to build axes
  function buildAxis(position,layer){
    var axis;
    var axisopts;
    if (!layer[position+"Axis"]){
      axisopts = opts[position+"Axis"];
    } else axisopts = layer[position+"Axis"];
    
    if(axisopts.measure) {
      axis = myChart[axisopts.type](position,layer[position],axisopts.measure);
    } else {
      axis = myChart[axisopts.type](position, layer[position]);
    };
    if(!(axisopts.type === "addPctAxis")) axis.showPercent = axisopts.showPercent;
    if (axisopts.orderRule) axis.addOrderRule(axisopts.orderRule);
    if (axisopts.grouporderRule) axis.addGroupOrderRule(axisopts.grouporderRule);  
    if (axisopts.overrideMin) axis.overrideMin = axisopts.overrideMin;
    if (axisopts.overrideMax) axis.overrideMax = axisopts.overrideMax;
    if (axisopts.inputFormat) axis.dateParseFormat = axisopts.inputFormat;
    if (axisopts.outputFormat) axis.tickFormat = axisopts.outputFormat;    
    return axis;
  };
  
  var c = null;
  if(d3.keys(opts.colorAxis).length > 0) {
    c = myChart[opts.colorAxis.type](opts.colorAxis.colorSeries,opts.colorAxis.palette) ;
  }
  
  //allow manipulation of default colors to use with dimple
  if(opts.defaultColors.length) {
    opts.defaultColors = opts.defaultColors[0];
    if (typeof(opts.defaultColors) == "function") {
      //assume this is a d3 scale
      //for now loop through first 20 but need a better way to handle
      defaultColorsArray = [];
      for (var n=0;n<20;n++) {
        defaultColorsArray.push(opts.defaultColors(n));
      };
      opts.defaultColors = defaultColorsArray;
    }
    opts.defaultColors.forEach(function(d,i) {
      opts.defaultColors[i] = new dimple.color(d);
    })
    myChart.defaultColors = opts.defaultColors;
  }  
  
  //do series
  //set up a function since same for each
  //as of now we have x,y,groups,data,type in opts for primary layer
  //and other layers reside in opts.layers
  function buildSeries(layer, hidden){
    //inherit from primary layer if not intentionally changed or xAxis, yAxis, zAxis null
    if (!layer.xAxis) layer.xAxis = opts.xAxis;    
    if (!layer.yAxis) layer.yAxis = opts.yAxis;
    if (!layer.zAxis) layer.zAxis = opts.zAxis;
    
    var x = buildAxis("x", layer);
    x.hidden = hidden;
    
    var y = buildAxis("y", layer);
    y.hidden = hidden;
    
    //z for bubbles
    var z = null;
    if (!(typeof(layer.zAxis) === 'undefined') && layer.zAxis.type){
      z = buildAxis("z", layer);
    };
    
    //here think I need to evaluate group and if missing do null
    //as the group argument
    //if provided need to use groups from layer
    var s = new dimple.series(myChart, null, x, y, z, c, null, dimple.plot[layer.type], dimple.aggregateMethod.avg, dimple.plot[layer.type].stacked);
    
    //as of v1.1.4 dimple can use different dataset for each series
    if(layer.data){
      //convert to an array of objects
      //avoid lodash for now
      datakeys = d3.keys(layer.data)
      layer.dataarray = layer.data[datakeys[1]].map(function(d,i){
        var tempobj = {}
        datakeys.forEach(function(key){
          tempobj[key] = layer.data[key][i]
        })
        return tempobj
      })
      s.data = layer.dataarray;
    }
    
    //for measure axis dimple sorts at the series level not at axis level
    ['x','y'].map(function(ax){
      if( layer[ax + 'Axis'].type=="addMeasureAxis" && layer[ax + 'Axis'].orderRule ){
        if( typeof layer[ax + 'Axis'].orderRule == "string" ){
          s.addOrderRule( layer[ax + 'Axis'].orderRule );
        } else if ( typeof layer[ax + 'Axis'].orderRule == "object" ) {
          s._orderRules = layer[ax + 'Axis'].orderRule;
        }
      }
    })
    
    if(layer.hasOwnProperty("groups")) {
      s.categoryFields = (typeof layer.groups === "object") ? layer.groups : [layer.groups];
      //series offers an aggregate method that we will also need to check if available
      //options available are avg, count, max, min, sum
    }
    if (!(typeof(layer.aggregate) === 'undefined')) {
      s.aggregate = eval(layer.aggregate);
    }
    if (!(typeof(layer.lineWeight) === 'undefined')) {
      s.lineWeight = layer.lineWeight;
    }
    if (!(typeof(layer.lineMarkers) === 'undefined')) {
      s.lineMarkers = layer.lineMarkers;
    }
    if (!(typeof(layer.barGap) === 'undefined')) {
      s.barGap = layer.barGap;
    }    
    if (!(typeof(layer.interpolation) === 'undefined')) {
      s.interpolation = layer.interpolation;
    } 
    
    myChart.series.push(s);
    
    /*placeholder fix domain of primary scale for new series data
    //not working right now but something like this
    //for now just use overrideMin and overrideMax from rCharts
    for( var i = 0; i<2; i++) {
      if (!myChart.axes[i].overrideMin) {
        myChart.series[0]._axisBounds(i==0?"x":"y").min = myChart.series[0]._axisBounds(i==0?"x":"y").min < s._axisBounds(i==0?"x":"y").min ? myChart.series[0]._axisBounds(i==0?"x":"y").min : s._axisBounds(i==0?"x":"y").min;
      }
      if (!myChart.axes[i].overrideMax) {  
        myChart.series[0]._axisBounds(i==0?"x":"y")._max = myChart.series[0]._axisBounds(i==0?"x":"y").max > s._axisBounds(i==0?"x":"y").max ? myChart.series[0]._axisBounds(i==0?"x":"y").max : s._axisBounds(i==0?"x":"y").max;
      }
      myChart.axes[i]._update();
    }
    */
      
    
    return s;
  };
  
  buildSeries(opts, false);
  if (opts.layers.length > 0) {
    opts.layers.forEach(function(layer){
      buildSeries(layer, true);
    })
  }
  //unsure if this is best but if legend is provided (not empty) then evaluate
  if(d3.keys(opts.legend).length > 0) {
    var l =myChart.addLegend();
    d3.keys(opts.legend).forEach(function(d){
      l[d] = opts.legend[d];
    });
  }
  //quick way to get this going but need to make this cleaner
  if(opts.storyboard) {
    myChart.setStoryboard(opts.storyboard);
  };
  myChart.draw();

</script>
